Dante's eight astrologers have moved from classical
through thirteenth-century exemplars, the recent ones in descending
nobility and literacy.  His list now declines to an anonymous plurality
of commonfolk, women who practice witchcraft through brewing magic
potions and making images of their clients' enemies.  For a detailed
study of Dante and magic see Simon Gilson, "Medieval Magical Lore and
Dante's ^Commedia~," ^Dante Studies~ 119 (2001), pp. 27-66.
